Syria U.S. controls have had minimal impact on industry because the U.S. Government does not require a license for most items for Syria's leading import sectors, including agricultural items and EAR99 products for the petroleum industry.
Despite recent setbacks to the Syrian economy, the economic reforms and infrastructure improvements undertaken by the government in the early 1990s, while limited, have enhanced the country's potential as a market for U.S. exports.
From 1992-2000, the volume of U.S. exports to Syria has been relatively stable, falling within the range of $161 million and $226 million per year.
In calendar year 2000, U.S. exports totaled $219.0 million.
Cereals, mostly corn, accounted for about a quarter of U.S. exports, as did various types of machinery.
Other leading exports included tobacco and pharmaceuticals.
The average annual value of export licenses issued by BXA for Syria has increased in the last ten years.
In FY 1991, BXA approved eight licenses with a total value of $1,041,504.
However, the value licensed trade has risen to an average of more than $83 million per year between FY 1994 through FY 2000.
In FY 2001 there was a decline in both the number of licenses approved for Syria as well as their value.
